{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606347"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:11:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:11:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15918"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15918"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48612"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7607"},{"type":"tags","id":"8682"},{"type":"tags","id":"8688"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the bipotential gonad can develop into either ovaries or testes. The subsequent development of internal reproductive structures depends on specific hormonal signals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is required for female reproductive tract development from M\u00fcllerian ducts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presence of XX chromosomes","Absence of anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone","Presence of oestrogen","Absence of testosterone receptors","Presence of follicle stimulating hormone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone (AMH)\u003C/strong\u003E is crucial for female reproductive tract development. Female development is considered the \u0027default\u0027 pathway - it occurs in the absence of male-specific factors (SRY gene, testosterone, and anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone). When anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone is absent, the M\u00fcllerian ducts persist and develop into the fallopian tubes, uterus, and upper vagina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of XX chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not sufficient, as evidenced by cases of complete androgen insensitivity syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of oestrogen\u003C/strong\u003E is not required for initial female tract development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of testosterone receptors\u003C/strong\u003E does not drive female development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of follicle stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is important for later ovarian function but not for initial tract development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The absence of SRY gene and testosterone allows female reproductive tract development","Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone causes regression of M\u00fcllerian ducts in male embryos","Female development is the default pathway in the absence of male-specific factors"],"references":["Rey R, Josso N, Racine C. Sexual Differentiation. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc. [Updated 2020 May 27]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279001/","Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48612"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15918"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48612"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T09:44:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T09:45:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8609"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63161"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":nu